Headlines.Headline: Bad News for U.S. Industry: China is Closing the Quality Gap

PARAGRAPH.#text: When it comes to competing against upstarts from China and other so-called emerging markets, U.S. makers of construction and mining equipment tend to say their trump card is quality: Sure, the American-designed machines cost more, but they also last longer, saving the customer money in the long haul.Rio Tinto, a London-based mining giant, put a dent in that notion this week. At an investor conference in London on Wednesday, Rio Tinto CEO Sam Walsh said his company has been increasing purchases of equipment and other items from China and India – and has found the quality impressive."It tends to be sophisticated purchases, which sort of is a little bit intriguing," Mr. Walsh said. Among the purchases were heavy-duty trucks, equipment for loading ships and rail cars that carry ore, he said. "Funnily enough, when the original ore cars came in and we evaluated those against the traditional supplier, the quality was actually much higher."More on this after the jump...

Europe's shaky economic health is already taking a toll on U.S. businesses. The Journal's Kate Linebaugh and Bob Sechler report that General Electric is going ahead with plans to restructure some of its operations to prepare for a possible European recession."We think it could get even tougher in Europe, and we are planning along those lines," says CEO Jeff Immelt.
Europe is deteriorating further today. Italy and Germany auctioned off bonds a couple hours ago and the sales highlighted the mixed fortunes within the EU. Italy was forced to pay a 6.47% yield, the highest on a five-year Italian auction in the euro era, while German two-year yields are sitting close to their record lows, Dow Jones Newswires says.
The euro is sliding -- it just dipped below $1.30, Italian borrowing costs are rising, and several EU leaders are warning that a treaty to bind member states closer fiscally will have a tough time getting through national parliaments, the FT notes.
